K9.fix_sketch:
Rust-only fix (Python is the reference implementation and already correct; byte-parity means Rust must match Python's csv.reader default dialect for the first field). In crates/clankerprof-core/src/rules.rs replace core_classes_from_csv's per-line split with a first-field parser honoring RFC-4180 quoting as Python's csv module does (quotechar '"', doubled-quote escape):

fn first_csv_field(line: &str) -> String {
    match line.strip_prefix('"') {
        None => line.split(',').next().unwrap_or("").to_string(),
        Some(rest) => {
            let mut out = String::new();
            let mut chars = rest.chars().peekable();
            while let Some(c) = chars.next() {
                if c == '"' {
                    if chars.peek() == Some(&'"') { out.push('"'); chars.next(); } else { break; }
                } else { out.push(c); }
            }
            out
        }
    }
}

fn core_classes_from_csv(payload: &str) -> BTreeSet<String> {
    payload.lines()
        .map(first_csv_field)
        .map(|value| value.trim().to_string())
        .filter(|value| !value.is_empty() && !value.starts_with('#'))
        .collect()
}

(Note Python applies .strip() AFTER csv parsing and the '#' check after strip — the order above mirrors that, so `"#foo"` is excluded in both languages.) Known residual edge: Python's csv.reader supports embedded newlines inside quoted fields and has non-strict mid-field-quote quirks; if full-fidelity is wanted, parse the whole payload with the `csv` crate (flexible mode) instead of per-line — but the minimal parser above covers all valid single-line CSVs, which is what the packaged file and documented workflow use. Accompany with: (a) a parity test in tests/test_clankerprof_rust_parity.py adding a --core-classes override file containing a quoted field (e.g. `"Array"`) to the targets flag matrix, and (b) a Rust unit test in rules.rs asserting core_classes_from_csv("\"Array\"\n") == {"Array"}. No Python change; no docs change needed beyond optionally noting override coverage in the parity matrix row/test column per the "must land in the Rust core and this parity suite in the same change" rule.

